---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';

import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Common Bingo Prefixes — RE, UN, OUT and More Scrabble Bingo Starters"
  description="Master the prefixes that unlock bingos in Scrabble. RE-, UN-, OUT-, OVER-, MIS- and more — learn which ones produce the most 7- and 8-letter words. Free."
  keywords="scrabble bingo prefixes, re words scrabble bingo, un prefix bingo, out prefix scrabble, common bingo starters, prefix strategy scrabble"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Common Bingo Prefixes — RE, UN, OUT and More Scrabble Bingo Starters",
    "description": "Master the prefixes that unlock bingos in Scrabble. RE-, UN-, OUT-, OVER-, MIS- and more.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "logo": { "@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/web-app-manifest-512x512.png" } },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/common-bingo-prefixes/" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What are the best prefixes for Scrabble bingos?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "RE- is the most productive bingo prefix, enabling over 500 valid 7-letter words in SOWPODS. UN- follows with 400+, then OUT- (200+), OVER- (150+), and MIS- (120+). These five prefixes alone account for roughly 25% of all playable bingos." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How do prefixes help you spot bingos?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "When you see RE or UN on your rack, mentally set those tiles aside and ask: do the remaining 5 tiles form a common word? If yes, you likely have a bingo. For example: RE + ASTING = REASTING, UN + SEALING = UNSEALING (too long, but UN + DOING = UNDOING)." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Can you play a bingo using a prefix already on the board?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — if RE is already played on the board and you can extend it with 7 tiles from your rack to form an 8+ letter word, you earn the bingo bonus. This is called playing through existing letters and is a powerful technique for prefix-based bingos." } }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/bingos/" class="hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors text-gray-300">Bingos</a>
      </nav>

      <BlogCrossLinks title="Common Bingo Prefixes" />


      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>7 min read</span>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">Prefixes are bingo shortcuts. When you spot RE, UN, or OUT on your rack, you're not searching through 25,000 possible 7-letter words — you're searching through the common 5-letter words those prefixes attach to. This drastically reduces your mental workload and speeds up bingo recognition.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Big Five Bingo Prefixes</h2>

      <p class="text-gray-300">These five prefixes produce the most valid bingos in both SOWPODS and TWL. Memorise them as your primary bingo-finding toolkit.</p>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Prefix</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">7-Letter Bingos</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Tiles Used</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Example Words</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-amber-400">RE-</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">500+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">R, E + 5</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">REUSING, RELATED, READING</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-amber-400">UN-</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">400+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">U, N + 5</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">UNRAISE, UNTRIED, UNLACED</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-amber-400">OUT-</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">200+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">O, U, T + 4</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">OUTRAISE, OUTSIDE, OUTRIDE</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-amber-400">OVER-</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">150+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">O, V, E, R + 3</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">OVERLIT, OVERTIP, OVERSAW</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-amber-400">MIS-</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400">120+</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">M, I, S + 4</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">MISRATE, MISLEAD, MISREAD</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">RE-</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">500+ bingos — #1 prefix</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25%</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">of all bingos use a prefix</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">5</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">prefixes to memorise</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">How to Use Prefixes on Your Rack</h2>

      <p class="text-gray-300">The mental process is simple: spot the prefix, isolate it, then ask whether the remaining tiles form a word.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Prefix Bingo Process</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Scan your rack for RE, UN, OUT, OVER, or MIS letter combinations.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Mentally set those tiles aside. Look at the remaining 4-5 tiles.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Can those remaining tiles anagram into a common word? STING, RATED, LACED, TRIED, DOING?</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">If yes → RESTRING, UNRATED, UNLACED, UNTRIED, UNDOING. Check if it's valid and fits the board.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Pro Tip</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Don't just check one prefix. Your rack UREINTS could be <span class="text-white font-medium">UN + RITES</span> (UNRITES? No) or <span class="text-white font-medium">RE + UNITS</span> (REUNITS? No) or just an anagram: <span class="text-white font-medium">UNITERS</span> (yes!). Always check prefix AND non-prefix solutions.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Secondary Prefixes Worth Knowing</h2>

      <p class="text-gray-300">Beyond the Big Five, these prefixes produce fewer bingos but appear frequently enough to be worth recognising:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">PRE- (80+ bingos)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">PRELOAD, PRESOAK, PRETEND, PREVAIL. Look for PRE when you have P, R, E together.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">DIS- (90+ bingos)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">DISRATE, DISROBE, DISMAY. Powerful but requires D, I, S — common tiles.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">IN- / IM- (70+ bingos)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">INSTATE, INFLATED, IMPASTE. Two tiles for a prefix makes this very efficient.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">EN- / EM- (60+ bingos)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">ENTAILS, ENSLAVE, EMPOWER. Short prefix, common tiles, many valid words.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/bingo-racks-to-memorise/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Bingo Racks to Memorise — the top 20 stems for rapid recognition</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/bingo-through-existing-letter/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Bingo Through an Existing Letter — extend prefixes already on the board</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/bingo-racks-to-memorise/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800 hover:border-amber-300 dark:hover:border-amber-700 hover:bg-amber-50/50 dark:hover:bg-amber-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-amber-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 group-hover:text-amber-600 dark:group-hover:text-amber-400 transition-colors">Bingo Racks to Memorise</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/spotting-bingos-on-your-rack/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800 hover:border-amber-300 dark:hover:border-amber-700 hover:bg-amber-50/50 dark:hover:bg-amber-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-amber-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 group-hover:text-amber-600 dark:group-hover:text-amber-400 transition-colors">Spotting Bingos on Your Rack</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/hook-words-advanced/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800 hover:border-amber-300 dark:hover:border-amber-700 hover:bg-amber-50/50 dark:hover:bg-amber-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-amber-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 group-hover:text-amber-600 dark:group-hover:text-amber-400 transition-colors">Hook Words Advanced</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-50 to-orange-50 dark:from-amber-900/20 dark:to-orange-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔤 Find prefix bingos from your tiles — free, instant, no signup</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 hover:bg-amber-600 text-white text-sm font-semibold transition-colors shadow-sm">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      
<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Building Your Word Arsenal</h2>

<p>The difference between a 300-point game and a 400-point game often comes down to vocabulary depth. Players who invest time studying valid Scrabble words consistently outscore those who rely solely on common everyday vocabulary. The words on this page represent a focused subset of the Scrabble dictionary that you can realistically memorise and deploy in competitive play.</p>

<p>Start by identifying which words on this page you already know. Then focus your study time on the unfamiliar ones — particularly those with high point values or unusual letter combinations. The goal is not to memorise the entire dictionary but to build a working vocabulary of 5,000-10,000 words that covers the most common game situations.</p>

<p>Consider keeping a word journal where you record new discoveries from each study session. Writing words down activates different memory pathways than simply reading them. Many tournament players carry small notebooks and review their most recent additions during breaks between rounds.</p>


<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Applying These Words in Real Games</h2>

<p>Knowing a word exists and successfully playing it in a game are two different skills. The bridge between them is pattern recognition — training your brain to spot opportunities for specific words when you see certain tile combinations on your rack. This comes through deliberate practice rather than passive memorisation.</p>

<p>When you study the words on this page, visualise how they would fit on a Scrabble board. Which premium squares could they reach? What letters would they need to hook onto? How many tiles from a typical rack would they consume? This kind of active visualisation builds the neural pathways that fire automatically during timed games.</p>

<p>One effective technique is to take each word and mentally construct the rack you would need to play it. Then ask yourself: if I drew those tiles, would I recognise the word opportunity immediately? If the answer is no, that word needs more study time. If yes, move on to the next unfamiliar word in your list.</p>

<p>Tournament players often practice with a specific study goal — for example, spending one week focused exclusively on 5-letter words containing a particular letter pattern, then the following week on 6-letter words. This structured approach prevents the overwhelm of trying to learn everything simultaneously.</p>


<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Advanced Rack Management</h2>

<p>Elite Scrabble players think in terms of rack leave — the tiles remaining after each play. A good rack leave balances vowels and consonants (ideally 3-4 consonants and 2-3 vowels), retains common letters like S, E, R, T, and avoids duplicates. Every word you play should be evaluated not just by its score but by what it leaves you to work with next turn.</p>

<p>The concept of synergy applies to Scrabble tiles just as it does to other games. Certain tile combinations work together beautifully — for example, holding ING or TION or NESS makes it easier to find 7-letter bingos. Conversely, holding double or triple copies of the same letter severely limits your options and often forces an exchange.</p>

<p>Tile tracking becomes increasingly important as the game progresses. By the midgame, you should have a rough idea of which high-value tiles remain in the bag. In the endgame (fewer than 7 tiles left in the bag), precise tracking allows you to deduce your opponent's exact rack and play accordingly — blocking their best plays while maximising your own remaining scoring opportunities.</p>

<p>Consider the concept of turnover — how many tiles you draw from the bag each turn. Playing 5-6 tiles per turn cycles through the bag faster, giving you more chances to draw premium tiles. Conversely, playing single-tile or two-tile words slows your turnover and reduces your overall access to the tile distribution across the full game.</p>

<div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a>
      </div>
    </article>
